> </tbody> </table> </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> <table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"100%\" class=\"m_-3325922716041993988mcnTextBlock\" style=\"min-width:100%;border-collapse:collapse\"> <tbody class=\"m_-3325922716041993988mcnTextBlockOuter\"> <tr> <td valign=\"top\" class=\"m_-3325922716041993988mcnTextBlockInner\" style=\"padding-top:9px\"> <table align=\"left\" border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"max-width:100%;min-width:100%;border-collapse:collapse\" width=\"100%\" class=\"m_-3325922716041993988mcnTextContentContainer\"> <tbody> <tr> <td valign=\"top\" class=\"m_-3325922716041993988mcnTextContent\" style=\"padding-top:0;padding-right:18px;padding-bottom:9px;padding-left:18px;word-break:break-word;color:#444444;font-family:'Source Sans Pro','Helvetica Neue',Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:16px;line-height:150%;text-align:left\"> One of the trends that we look for in this project is the timing of peak abundance of caterpillars, meaning the point in the season when we are finding caterpillars most frequently. It turns out there are several noticeable peaks over the summer in North Carolina that are roughly consistent from year to year: one in late May, one in mid-June, one in late June, and perhaps another in mid-July. These peaks likely correspond to different sets of caterpillar species which tend to emerge earlier or later in the summer. </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> <table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" width=\"100%\" class=\"m_-3325922716041993988mcnCaptionBlock\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse\"> <tbody class=\"m_-3325922716041993988mcnCaptionBlockOuter\"> <tr> <td class=\"m_-3325922716041993988mcnCaptionBlockInner\" valign=\"top\" style=\"padding:9px\"> <table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"m_-3325922716041993988mcnCaptionRightContentOuter\" width=\"100%\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse\"> <tbody> <tr> <td valign=\"top\" cla